While you're at improving ForEach-Object -Parallel please address this:

Doesn't work

```powershell
$OhMy = 'Test'
(1..100) | ForEach-Object -Parallel {
    $Test = $Using:OhMy
    (1..50) | ForEach-Object -Parallel {
        $Test5 = $Using:Test
    }
}
```

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15063294/74090909-8d638d80-4ab1-11ea-8f60-f55be0ae2792.png)


Works:
```powershell
$OhMy = 'Test'
$Test = $null
(1..100) | ForEach-Object -Parallel {
    $Test = $Using:OhMy
    (1..50) | ForEach-Object -Parallel {
        $Test5 = $Using:Test
    }
}
```

# Summary of the new feature/enhancement

Currently there isn't much you can do with `System.Memory<T>` other than create it, pass it to a method and allocate a new array from it.  Most of the functionality is actually attached to the property `Span` which PowerShell is unable to use.

While this type might not be incredibly applicable to PowerShell users today, it is going to be utilized more and more by the framework itself and third party libs as time goes on. Some basic support for at least enumerating and accessing by index would go a long way.

# Proposed technical implementation details (optional)

Special casing in the binder should be added to enable either direct indexing of `System.Memory` 

```powershell
$memory = [Memory[int]][int[]](0..10)

# Should return 0
$memory[0]

# Should set index 0 to 1
$memory[0] = 1

# Should enumerate
foreach ($i in $memory) {
}
```

<details>

<summary><sub>Alternate, more complicated proposal</sub></summary>

Or specifically for indexing, enable the usage of `System.Span` *when accessed directly from `Memory`*.  This might be the most idea route for understandably (since `Memory` doesn't have an indexer) but might also be impossible with how the binder is set up.

```powershell
$memory = [Memory[int]][int[]](0..10)

# Should return 0
$memory.Span[0]

# Should set index 0 to 1
$memory.Span[0] = 1

# This will still throw
foreach ($i in $memory.Span) {
}

# This will still throw
$i = $memory.Span
$i[0]
```

</details>

